00:21:06,734 --> 00:21:09,095
I'm doing something that's kind of vague. It's sort of a hint.

496
00:21:09,755 --> 00:21:12,816
And so in this game, you're hinting at the ship what you want to do.

497
00:21:12,956 --> 00:21:16,397
But you can make big gestures if you move both your thumbs at the same time.

498
00:21:16,577 --> 00:21:18,478
But really, most of the time, you're just hinting at it.

499
00:21:18,958 --> 00:21:20,739
And because you have to hint at it a lot,

500
00:21:21,039 --> 00:21:23,700
the player has to make a lot of decisions all the time.

501
00:21:24,080 --> 00:21:25,820
And that takes a lot of the stress out.

502
00:21:26,241 --> 00:21:31,207
of what those decisions are, which is really, really helpful.

503
00:21:32,564 --> 00:21:37,685
for the player. And it makes you able to free up your visual perception, to pay attention

504
00:21:37,725 --> 00:21:41,526
to all of these tons and tons of asteroids that are moving, which you would normally

505
00:21:41,566 --> 00:21:45,807
not be able to do. If this was a dual stick game, you'd be paying so much attention to

506
00:21:45,847 --> 00:21:49,847
where your ship was and if it ended up where you wanted it to be, that you wouldn't be

507
00:21:49,907 --> 00:21:53,308
able to pay attention to how these asteroids are moving. If you notice here, there are

508
00:21:53,388 --> 00:21:57,589
no visual cues as to where those asteroids are going. You actually have to keep track

509
00:21:57,609 --> 00:21:59,869
of them and remember where they were.

510
00:22:02,430 --> 00:22:05,011
Okay, so that was a lot of different things that I covered,

511
00:22:05,051 --> 00:22:07,312
and probably you're not going to remember all of them exactly.

512
00:22:07,372 --> 00:22:11,513
So I'll sum it up in a couple ways that should be helpful.

513
00:22:11,993 --> 00:22:13,594
So the first thing, if you're going to do this,

514
00:22:13,714 --> 00:22:15,474
is you need to be flexible with your game design.

515
00:22:15,934 --> 00:22:18,395
You need to understand that games are as much a product

516
00:22:18,535 --> 00:22:22,136
as of the interaction possibilities of the platform

517
00:22:22,176 --> 00:22:23,236
that you're developing for,

518
00:22:24,897 --> 00:22:26,457
as they are of your own creativity.

519
00:22:26,857 --> 00:22:30,539
And it's actually normal and great to let controls

520
00:22:30,639 --> 00:22:32,119
influence the direction of your game.

521
00:22:32,873 --> 00:22:34,134
This is incredibly common.

522
00:22:34,494 --> 00:22:36,116
So a genre that works on a controller

523
00:22:36,256 --> 00:22:37,757
might not be viable on a touchscreen,

524
00:22:37,897 --> 00:22:39,239
might not be viable on a Wii.

525
00:22:39,739 --> 00:22:40,300
That's okay.

526
00:22:42,021 --> 00:22:43,723
The other thing is you need to be really serious

527
00:22:43,763 --> 00:22:44,964
about thinking about these things.

528
00:22:45,524 --> 00:22:46,986
Controls are really important.

529
00:22:47,346 --> 00:22:48,787
They're the way that we're interacting

530
00:22:49,007 --> 00:22:50,289
with the games that are playing.

531
00:22:50,449 --> 00:22:52,711
And if you're not paying attention to it,

532
00:22:52,991 --> 00:22:55,093
you're really doing a disservice to all the creativity

533
00:22:55,133 --> 00:22:56,734
that you've put into your game in the first place.

534
00:22:57,598 --> 00:23:01,419
A skilled player needs to be able to know what the input that they give to a virtual

535
00:23:01,459 --> 00:23:03,320
environment will do before they see it.

536
00:23:04,520 --> 00:23:07,921
Just like when you walk down the street, you don't hope that you're not going to fall over,

537
00:23:08,101 --> 00:23:08,441
you know.

538
00:23:08,841 --> 00:23:12,022
And that's how we need to be able to interact with everything in a game.

539
00:23:12,302 --> 00:23:17,144
And then the last one is once you have good feeling controls, once you have players who

540
00:23:17,164 --> 00:23:21,085
are confident, you need to make sure your game supports them, that it supports the strengths

541
00:23:21,125 --> 00:23:24,806
of the controls and not the weaknesses, that it integrates those two things well.

542
00:23:25,442 --> 00:23:27,763
So this stuff isn't rocket scientist science.

543
00:23:28,244 --> 00:23:30,265
Well, it's not made by rocket scientists.

544
00:23:31,706 --> 00:23:34,388
And it just requires a little bit of time

545
00:23:34,548 --> 00:23:36,029
and a little bit of experimentation

546
00:23:36,510 --> 00:23:37,570
and these three things.

547
00:23:37,630 --> 00:23:39,111
And when you get it right, there's nothing better

548
00:23:39,552 --> 00:23:41,333
because your controls become invisible.

549
00:23:41,533 --> 00:23:43,434
And instead of concentrating on your controls,

550
00:23:43,695 --> 00:23:45,736
players concentrate on playing the hell out of your game.

551
00:23:46,617 --> 00:23:49,739
Also, these are good points for being a good human being.

552
00:23:49,839 --> 00:23:52,381
That's totally unrelated, but I think it's important.

553
00:23:53,582 --> 00:23:54,382
OK, so thanks.

554
00:23:54,562 --> 00:23:55,083
That's my talk.

